	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>In the spotlight: activities of EU fleets fishing for small pelagics in third-country waters </h1>

			
			<h4>
												18 March 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Various reports have drawn attention to issues arising from the activities of the EU fleet fishing for small pelagics, represented by the association PFA (Pelagic Freezer Association). PFA represents nine companies and 25 EU-flagged fishing vessels, operating for part of the year in EU waters, and for another part in West African and South Pacific waters.</p><p>In early January 2012, a report commissioned by Greenpeace described the direct and indirect EU funding for PFA members. For the period 1994-2006 they received subsidies worth €45.7 million (from FIFG funds). For the period 2007-2010 they only received €1.1 million (from EFF funds): ‘This lower amount is probably caused by the stronger focus of EU funding on sustainable fishing methods’, according to the report, adding that ‘Moreover, the members of the PFA have received a very high estimated share of the total support provided by the EU under Morocco and Mauritania FPAs’. A Greenpeace representative commented that ‘PFA ships are literally floating fish factories, capable of catching, processing and freezing 300 tonnes of fish a day … This is putting the food security of millions of West African people at risk ... it’s effectively the European taxpayer who is subsidising the large scale removal of fish from their seas – fish that never make it to their plates’.</p><p>Meanwhile, the ICIJ published a report in the <i>New York Times</i> showing that stocks of small pelagics in the southern Pacific, also targeted by PFA fleets and others, have been decimated in the last two decades. Recently, in order to stake claims for jack mackerel quotas in the emerging South Pacific RFMO, trawlers have arrived <i>en masse</i>. One of these trawlers, at one time the world’s biggest fishing vessel, is the Atlantic Dawn, which formerly fished in Mauritania. ICIJ reports that the president of the PFA confirmed that ‘vessels fished too hard at a time when jack mackerel stocks were on a natural downward cycle … There was way too big an effort in too short a time … The entire fleet, including the Pelagic Freezer-Trawler Association, has to be blamed for it.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>‘Direct and indirect EU support for the members of the Pelagic Freezer-Trawler Association (PFA)’, a research paper prepared for Stichting Greenpeace by Profundo economic research, January 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.greenpeace.nl/Global/nederland/report/2011/Direct%20and%20indirect%20EU%20support%20PFA.pdf" target="_self">http://www.greenpeace.nl/Global/nederland/report/2011/Direct%20and%20ind...</a></p><p>Greenpeace UK blog on fisheries, 23 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/blog/oceans/how-much-im-paid-tax-payers-money-20111223" target="_self">http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/blog/oceans/how-much-im-paid-tax-payers-mon...</a></p><p>Press article, ‘“Free for all” decimates fish stocks in southern Pacific’, ICIJ in <i>New York Times</i>, 25 January 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.iwatchnews.org/2012/01/25/7900/free-all-decimates-fish-stocks-southern-pacific " target="_self">http://www.iwatchnews.org/2012/01/25/7900/free-all-decimates-fish-stocks...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>As is shown by these reports, EU fleets fishing for small pelagics are highly mobile, moving between EU, West African and South Pacific waters. The reduction of fishing possibilities in some of their fishing grounds, including EU waters (where recuperation plans for small pelagic stocks are in place), or South Pacific waters (where a decision has just been taken by the South Pacific RFMO to decrease quotas), means that more pressure will be exerted by these fleets to maintain or extend fishing possibilities in alternative fishing grounds like West Africa. However, with the non-renewal of the EU-Morocco agreement, it is not clear how such an increase in fishing possibilities could be achieved, either through fishing agreements or through private licensing. ACP states need to adopt a precautionary approach concerning the access of this fleet to their waters. Small pelagics are strategic stocks (particularly for direct food security in West Africa), and allowing too great a fishing effort at times when these stocks, whose abundance varies greatly from one year to the next, would be on a natural downward cycle could rapidly lead to overfishing.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

